<span style="font-size: 12pt;">Stevenson 12-12</span> (Matthew Stevenson, contributing editor of Harper’s Magazine, published in Forbes, the International Herald Tribune, and American Scholar, “The Coming Middle East War,” The New York Times Examiner, 12-3-2012, http://www.nytexaminer.com/2012/12/the-coming-middle-east-war/)
<span style="font-size: 8pt;">Following the maxim that to have peace it’s best to prepare for war, I thought it useful to speculate on the possibility that </span>the Middle East could <span class="StyleBoldUnderline">erupt into a wider conflict, </span>pull<span class="StyleBoldUnderline">ing into its vortex</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> many regional powers, not to mention </span>//Russia, China, and the U//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">nited </span>//S//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">tates.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> My fear is that </span>the region is //on the brink// of<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> a </span>catastrophe<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> and that for months the clues leading up to this wider war have been delivered every day on our doorsteps. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">The reason that the evidence is not clearer is because, with so much information to process from Syria, Gaza, and beyond, most of us reach whatever conclusions that we already have, which makes it that much harder to connect the dots on other possibilities</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Instead of coming to bury the New York Times, on this occasion I choose to praise it, for dropping hints, allusions, references, and asides that someday may form the smoking gun trail, should the Middle East erupt into a broad war, Armageddon so to speak.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> WASHINGTON — </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">The</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> American </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">effort to stem the flow of Iranian arms to Syria has faltered</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> because of Iraq’s reluctance to inspect aircraft carrying the weapons through its airspace, American officials say.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> The shipments have persisted at a critical time for President Bashar al-Assad of Syria, who has come under increasing military pressure from rebel fighters. The air corridor over Iraq has emerged as a main supply route for weapons, including rockets, antitank missiles, rocket-propelled grenade and mortars.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Iran has an enormous stake in Syria</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, which is its staunchest Arab ally and has also provided a channel for Iran’s support to the Lebanese Islamist movement Hezbollah.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> To the disappointment of the Obama administration, American efforts to persuade the Iraqis to randomly inspect the flights have been largely unsuccessful.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> —New York Times December 1, 2012: “Flow of Arms to Syria Through Iraq Persists, to U.S. Dismay.”</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">If a royal assassination in the Balkans could touch off the Great War, certainly </span>//the combination of the Arab Spring, civil wars in Libya and Syria//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline">, great power interventions in </span>//Afghanistan and Iraq, suppression in Gaza//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline">, drones in action, </span>//and the specter of a nuclear Iran could lead to escalation//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> on fronts that stretch </span>//from the shores of Tripoli to Kashmir//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">An Arab rising in the West Bank and Gaza, supported by Egypt, coupled with a conventional war on the Lebanese border—</span>//routine events//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> in the Middle East in recent years—</span>might be //all the ingredients needed to trigger a wider war//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">. Plato said that “only the dead have seen the end of war” without ever having surveyed the modern Middle East, with artificial borders that are a legacy of colonial mapmakers.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Moreover, a truism of the Arab Spring is that violent rebellion works, so long as you can get the big guns on your side. Take Libya: Muammar Gaddafi fell because the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) wanted his scalp. Had Russia been on his side, he might have survived or lasted as long as Bashar al-Assad.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> *</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> WASHINGTON — The Pentagon has told the Obama administration that any military effort to seize Syria’s stockpiles of chemical weapons would require upward of 75,000 troops, amid increasing concern that the militant group Hezbollah has set up small training camps close to some of the chemical weapons depots, according to senior American officials.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> —NYT, November 12, 2012</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">A wider war could well start around</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> the Litani River, a small, meandering stream that bisects </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">southern Lebanon</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, south of which is Hezbollah’s military heartland, hard against the north border of Israel.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Hezbollah is a hybrid political, charitable and terrorist organization, and has more guns than the Lebanese National Army and pipelines of money and weaponry from Syria and Iran. It has become the leading political party in Lebanon, putting it at odds with Sunni and Christian interests there, not to mention Israel.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">One reason the Syrian civil war is so violent and prolonged is that it has become a proxy battle for the power that will dominate</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> the headwaters of the Litani around Mount Hermon and Shebaa Farms, where the River Jordan also has its well springs.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> If President Assad, together with his patrons in Tehran, manages to hang on in Syria, Hezbollah can continue to influence Lebanon and pressure Israel. An Assad defeat, especially to the Saudi-Qatari coalition, and Hezbollah will die on the vines of southern Lebanon, perhaps those clipped with a follow-up Israeli invasion.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">If only to deflect the coalition mounting against him</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, President </span>Assad <span class="StyleBoldUnderline">could well open another front against Israel</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">He has shown few qualms about using power and assassination to assert influence in Lebanon</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, and I could easily see him </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">enflaming that troubled nation in a last ditch-effort to stay in power</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> No wonder </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">it is reported</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> (November 28, 2012) </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">that he</span> is readying the use of chemical weapons<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> against the rebels</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, although that could be the Saddam ruse to justify a NATO deployment:</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> The most urgent decision, likely to come next week, is whether NATO should deploy surface-to-air missiles in Turkey, ostensibly to protect that country from Syrian missiles that could carry chemical weapons. The State Department spokeswoman, Victoria Nuland, said Wednesday that the Patriot missile system would not be “for use beyond the Turkish border.”</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> *</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">The regional </span>struggle for power in Syria could<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> well </span>escalate<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> into a larger firefight between Shiite powers (Assad, Iraq, Iran, and Hezbollah) and a Sunni bloc that includes Turkey, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and Jordan</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. All have strong reasons for not wanting the other side to prevail in Syria, but those differences might blur if Israel or the United States were involved in the fighting.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> About all that the Arab countries of the Middle East can agree upon is a hatred of Israel, and the recent sound-and-light success of Hamas in its border skirmishes shows other factions that Israel’s conventional approach to war (tanks, rockets, and infantry) matches up poorly against street demonstrators with rocks and homemade missiles.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Ironically, in Syria, Israel has more interest in keeping Assad in power than in seeing a Saudi-dominated government in Damascus. That regime might squeeze Hezbollah, but it could well agitate more forcefully for a return of the Golan Heights and confrontation with Israel—something Assad has only done symbolically.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Nor is it clear how Egypt would respond if there is a cross-border war between Israel and Hezbollah or conflict with its patrons in Iran and Syria. My guess is that Hamas would use such a moment to open a second front and that Cairo would have a hard time staying out of a broader conflict that featured Arabs and Israelis, even though they would have serious pressure from the United States to stand down.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Israel’s existential threat would come from a war in which it was attacked from Syria, Lebanon, Egypt, and Iran. In such a battle, the United States would side with Israel, although I cannot see the Obama administration committing ground troops to another Middle East war, even if Israel were suffering reversals.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> *</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Iran’s foreign minister, Ali Akbar Salehi, also addressed the gathering, warning that outside interference could incite violence throughout the region. Arming the opposition would only aggravate the crisis, SANA quoted him as saying.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> France broached the idea last week of lifting the arms embargo on Syria, saying it was studying the idea of helping the rebels. In general, Western nations have avoided providing weapons.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> —NYT, November 18, 2012</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span>//Balkan dominoes apply//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> to the Middle East </span>//because many of the great powers have client states//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> or groups </span>in the region<span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Russia</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, possibly China, </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">has</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> President </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Assad</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">The U</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">nited </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">S</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">tates </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">has Israel</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Turkey, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia have the Syrian rebels</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Egypt has Hamas</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Syria and Iran have Hezbollah</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">None of these powers wants to see its allies vanquished</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> One reason that the United States invaded Iraq was that it hoped to drive a Western wedge between the axis of evil that joins Syria and Iran. Ironically, it restored to power a Shiite majority that has more sympathy with Assad and Hezbollah, not to mention Tehran, than with its liberators in Washington. For the moment, Shiite influence runs on a line from Tehran to Hezbollah.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> *</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">For many in the Middle East, </span>//escalation against Israel could be an easier option than doing nothing//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> and awaiting defeat on a piecemeal basis</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. In facing Hamas, the Palestinian Authority, and Hezbollah—not to mention Assad and the Egyptian Muslim Brotherhood—</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Israel’s strategy has been to divide and rule along its precarious borders. That option disappears if its enemies find themselves coordinating attacks in a wider, regional conflict</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> There were reports on Sunday of a minor exchange of fire across the border with Israel in the Golan Heights, the third such episode reported this month, and of an artillery shell landing in Jordan.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> —NYT, November 18, 2012</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">In an enflamed border war, for example around the Golan Heights</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, I could well </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">imagine Iran supporting its Syrian coalition, with arms and money, if not with ships and missiles</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Such a conflict would certainly enflame the West Bank and Gaza, bringing Egypt closer to engagement</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Turkey</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> would prefer to stay out of such a fight, unless the disintegration of Syria caused a rebellion for Kurdish independence; then it </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">would be all-in</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Russia would not be eager for attacks against Israel that could lead to a confrontation with the United States, but, as in Syria today, it could be counted on to defeat UN resolutions and supply weapons to losing sides.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> *</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Another reason to fear broader regional war is because </span>//the U//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">nited </span>//S//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">tates </span>//looks adrift//on desert sands<span style="font-size: 8pt;">. Iran has managed to navigate the shoals of its nuclear development without suffering major consequences. Russia and China have picked up the slack of the international sanctions, and the United States and Israel disagree on any military option.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Diplomatically, the weakness of Obama can be seen in the wandering mission</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> of Secretary of State Hillary Clinton </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">to mediate the crisis in Gaza</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. She posed for pictures in Jerusalem, the West Bank, and Cairo but, </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">since the U.S. will not speak with Hamas</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, had little say in the terms of the cease-fire, as described by Rami Khouri in the Daily Star (Beirut):</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Perhaps the most significant aspect of the Gaza cease-fire this week was Egypt taking the lead role in mediating that agreement that ended the fighting, while the United States softly shuffled to the side. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Unlike Libya, when the U.S. said it was “leading from behind,” in this case</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">, with Secretary of State Hilary Clinton’s last-minute entry into the picture, </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">the U.S. was more like “following from the front.” </span>Washington <span class="StyleBoldUnderline">remains influential in the Middle East but is </span>//no longer the maestro//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> leading the diplomatic orchestra; instead it </span>//must now coordinate its policies// more practically //with//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> other players in the region, especially</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Egypt and </span>//Turkey//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">. Clinton had much to be thankful for on Thanksgiving Thursday, when she could get out of the Middle East after spending a few days in the region more or less looking hapless. She showed what it means to be a lame duck – in her own capacity and reflecting America’s foreign policy in the region.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span>//Nor does the U//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">nited </span>//S//<span style="font-size: 8pt;">tates </span>//have much leverage//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> in Syria, Iraq, Libya, or Egypt</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Turkey has staked out a diplomatic course that is independent of NATO and Washington</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. Pakistan remains livid about the drone campaign, and Kabul is in a holding pattern until the Americans withdraw and the Taliban returns.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> *</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> The irony of the Obama administration is that, despite many headlines, it has little identity in the Middle East, except for the drone campaigns and assassinations.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> For a while it worked. As Mr. Obama’s newly fallen director of central intelligence, David H. Petraeus, asked so succinctly a year ago, “Who wouldn’t want a light-footprint strategy?”</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> But implicit in Mr. Petraeus’s arch question was the recognition that the strategy has limited utility. And </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">now Mr. Obama is under more pressure than ever to become engaged in the Middle East</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> in a way that he avoided during the presidential campaign. In his own party, there are rumblings that he should intervene more directly to halt the slaughter in Syria — by placing Patriot missiles around the region to take down President Bashar al-Assad’s air power — and to renew efforts in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process as soon as the current missile barrages can be contained.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> —NYT, November 17, 2012</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">No one is clear if the U.S. is for or against Israeli policies</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> (especially with new settlements), </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">a friend or critic of</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> the </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Saudi expansion</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> in Syria, </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">the benefactors or opposition of Egypt’s Muslim Brotherhood, or the deterrent of nuclear expansion in Iran</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Depending where you look, the U.S. is either the beacon of democracy or just another</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Middle East </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">strongman</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">In Iraq, Bahrain, Gaza, and Afghanistan, the U.S. opposes opposition voices</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Conversely, it encourages dissent in Libya, Egypt, and Syria</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">. </span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">In Yemen, Afghanistan, and Pakistan, it prefers drone violence over diplomacy</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span class="StyleBoldUnderline">Such </span>discrepancies<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> hardly add up to a coherent policy that </span>can be quickly understoodby friends and foes alike<span class="StyleBoldUnderline">—</span>another reason to fear //miscalculation//<span class="StyleBoldUnderline"> leading to a bigger war</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;">.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> The argument over “Benghazi” is shorthand for American confusion absent whether winter or summer will follow the Arab Spring. The Republicans see al-Qaeda behind many sand dunes.The Obama administration hopes that more democratic governments in Libya, Egypt, and possibly Syria, along with its sanctions against Iran, will usher in a period of regional stability.</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Equally probable is that some aggrieved party may utter, “Cry ‘Havoc!’ and let slip the dogs of war,” in a manner that takes the Western world by surprise by the expanse of the fighting. How could Turkey, Iran, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, the Palestinians, Iraq, the Kurds, and Israel not become entangled in an escalating regional war?</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">¶</span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> The military historian John Keegan wrote that in August 1914, “War came out of a cloudless sky, to populations which knew almost nothing of it and had been raised to doubt that it could ever again trouble their continent.” In the Middle East, we already know it’s overcast and rainy, with a good chance of gale force winds. </span>

